         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">31/5/77. ¶  ¶ I admire the vigor &amp; unceasing steadiness of your researches, dear Mr Bentham; but then you are in happy independence and there is nothing to withdraw your attention from your glorious c...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">77.05.31</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew Correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, ff. 195-196.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">31/5/77.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I admire the vigor &amp; unceasing steadiness of your researches, dear Mr Bentham; but then you are in happy independence and there is nothing to withdraw your attention from your glorious course of observations. As you ask so,<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Request not found.</p>
               </note> it is pleasing to record, that the cases with the Museum plants (now approximately 70) have travelled to &amp; fro all right hitherto since the last 15 years except one with <name key="Leguminosae">Leguminosae</name>, the contents of which were in part sadly damaged by seawater, as mentioned at the time.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to W. Hooker, 25 August 1864 (as 64-08-25d), and M to G. Bentham, 24 September 1864.</p>
               </note> Let me hope, that the <name key="Gramineae">Gramineae</name>, <name key="Cyperaceae">Cyperaceae</name> and <name key="Filices">Filices</name> will also come all safely back. This final discussion on this subject incites a wish of mine. Pray ask Dr Hooker, that in bare justice to me in my still continued departmental oppression, it may be distinctly mentioned in his next report, that an enormous number of species of Australian plants became, so I must assume, deposited in Kew from the collections of my Museum, while they passed through your hands. </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>What do you think of my "select plants".<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B76 12.04. </p>
               </note> It has been a work of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">protracted toil</hi>
               </seg>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Had I not been excluded from my Garden, the 300 pages by my daily Directorial observations and acquisitions might have advanced to 600.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Why does Mr Baker subordinate the <name key="Cordyline%20Murchisoniae">Cordyline Murchisoniae</name> to C. Haageana.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Baker (1875), p. 541-2. </p>
               </note> Is there a misprint concerning the year of Koch's Wochenschrift.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M published <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Cordyline murchisoniae</seg> in B66.12.04, p. 195, while Koch published <seg style="font-style: italic; ">C. Haageana </seg>in W. Koch (1867), p. 195, the date given by Baker. Bentham (1863-78), vol. 7, p. 22, followed Baker (1875) and used Koch’s name.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Like you I spent many months on the <name key="Cyperaceae">Cyperaceae</name>,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">G. Bentham to M, 10 January 1877. </p>
               </note> and my work was rendered difficult all the more, because the labourious researches of Boeckeler<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Boeckeler (1868-77), or to the series of articles in <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Linnaea</seg> that were later consolidated (see TL2, title number 580).</p>
               </note> came under my notice only, after I had completed nearly the whole of my observations.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B74 11.01, pp. 255-74; B75.02.01, p. 6-22; B75.03.01, pp. 23-40.</p>
               </note> In <name key="Scleropus">Scleropus</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Error for <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Sphaeropus?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> I could neither see anything else than <name key="Scleria%20pygmaea">Scleria pygmaea</name>. When it is considered how variable the position of the sterile or male flowers is in other genera of <name key="Cyperaceae">Cyperaceae</name> (e.g. <name key="Carex">Carex</name>) it will be difficult to assign to them generic value for <name key="Gahnia">Gahnia</name> &amp; <name key="Cladium">Cladium</name>, which two united (to my mind) form a very natural genus. Here arises this trouble. So long as we have one well marked genus, we know at once in the field at first sight what genus name to give; whereas, if you finally adopt your limitation as more than subgeneric, one has to pull the spikelets on every occasion asunder, before the name can be assigned, for to <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">remember</hi>
               </seg> it would be almost impossible in most instances. </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Now genera are all artificial, species only natural; the former only formed to aid our memory. Hence I always keep the genera as large as I can, to simplify the systematic naming. On this path I follow Poiret and Sprengel to unite <name key="Isolepis">Isolepis</name> with <name key="Scirpus">Scirpus</name> and also <name key="Chaetospora">Chaetospora</name> with <name key="Schoenus">Schoenus</name>;<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See for example, Sprengel (1820-22), vol. 3, pp. 8, 10; Poiret (1810-17), vol. 2, p. 251.</p>
               </note> if I adhered to R Browns nomenclature,<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Mostly from R. Brown (1810).</p>
               </note> it was simply because it is here most in vogue, altho' at pages 36 &amp; 38 of vol. IX fragmenta<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B75.03.01.</p>
               </note> and in others of my writings I approved of Sprengels &amp; already Poiret's views. </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>From North Queensland I have now also a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Miliusia">Miliusia</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>.<note xml:id="ftn13" type="footnote" n="13">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">In B89.12.03, p. 5, the entry for <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Miliusia">Miliusia</name>
                     </seg> is 'species undetermined'.</p>
               </note> (How is <name key="Phaeanthus">Phaeanthus</name> really to be distinguished?)</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I shall watch with interest the arrival of the pages of the last volume,<note xml:id="ftn14" type="footnote" n="14">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham (1863-78), vol. 7.</p>
               </note> and I trust that then your time will otherwise untaxed to bring the most important of all your works, the "genera"<note xml:id="ftn15" type="footnote" n="15">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> to a conclusion.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Always with regardful attachment your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
